	<div class="intro-section">
		<p class="lead">Living near busy roads, commercial areas, or noisy neighbors can significantly impact your enjoyment of outdoor spaces. While no fence can completely eliminate noise, the right fence design can meaningfully reduce sound levels in your Stockton yard. This guide explains how noise-reducing fences work and what options are available.</p>
	</div>

	<h2>How Fences Reduce Noise</h2>
	<p>Understanding sound behavior helps you make informed decisions:</p>

	<h3>Sound Blocking vs. Sound Absorption</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Blocking:</strong> Dense materials prevent sound from passing through</li>
		<li><strong>Absorption:</strong> Soft/textured materials absorb sound waves</li>
		<li><strong>Diffusion:</strong> Irregular surfaces scatter sound waves</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Key Principles</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Mass matters:</strong> Heavier, denser materials block more sound</li>
		<li><strong>Height helps:</strong> Taller barriers block more noise</li>
		<li><strong>No gaps:</strong> Sound travels through any opening</li>
		<li><strong>Distance matters:</strong> Closer to noise source = more effective</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Realistic Expectations</h2>
	<p>A quality noise-reducing fence can typically reduce perceived noise by 5-10 decibels. In practice, this means:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Noticeable reduction in traffic noise</li>
		<li>Conversations become harder to hear</li>
		<li>Lower frequencies (bass) are harder to block</li>
		<li>High-pitched sounds are easier to reduce</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>What Fences CAN'T Do</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Eliminate noise completely</li>
		<li>Block sounds that travel over the fence</li>
		<li>Stop very low-frequency vibrations</li>
		<li>Reduce noise from above (aircraft, etc.)</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Best Materials for Noise Reduction</h2>

